text: In the original movie, Julie Andrews brings across her character as Mary Poppins with such incredible depth and strength of polished professional and robust solidarity, it seems that any attempts by other actresses (Emily Blunt) to step into her role will come across as watery and inferior by comparison. Compare the voices of Emily Blunt to Julie Andrews.. Their Tones of voice... Emily Blunt makes a decent attempt but even just her voice tones are not quite strong or deep enough, lacking the weightyness beind it, needed by the character to portray that role, to convince that she is the almighty Mary Poppins.. However I'm intrigued and I look forward to seeing what the movie is in its entirety. Some excellent members of cast just to pull out some extra stops. Long live Julie Andrews - The One and Only Mary Poppins.

text: I tired watching this movie and lasted 5 minutes. In that time Disney gave us the following lessons on political correctness. 1. We have a black milkman, in 1910, mmmm.  2. We have the 21 century millennial white male in the Banks brother, simpering, weak and inept. 3. The sister, by contrast is strong and, of course, liberal and, I assume, a feminist. 4. The nasty white previous generation male lawyer, full of entitlement and arrogance with his black side kick, to whom he is a little diffident, who is gentle and kind, although he knows nothing about the case. Said black lawyer sports a double barrelled name. LOL. In 5 minutes, we have been  fed inclusiveness, useless white men, strong, liberal, feminist women, entitled men with white privileged, who are borderline racist and black men who are the polar opposite. I didn't feel like spending 2 hours being spoon fed political correctness, so I gave up on the film. Actually, i watch very few movies now because this seems to be the trend now across the board, most female American actors are on steroids and testosterone. Perhaps there should be a new Oscar award, "Most politically correct movie."
